The paper discusses the development of a novel architecture for enabling humanoid robots to detect and recognize objects in real-time, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of deep learning for object detection and recognition suggests that the paper could also belong to computer vision (cs.CV) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The modifications made to the YOLOv3 algorithm and the use of neural nets for guiding the robot's actions indicate that the paper could also be relevant to machine learning (cs.LG) and multi-agent systems (cs.MA) sub-categories.
